While an experimental vaccine appears to be able to reduce Ebola mortality, there are currently no drugs that have been conclusively proven to be effective for treating existing infections.
An antibody cocktail, ZMapp, initially proved to be promising, but formal studies showed that it brought less benefits than hoped for in terms of preventing deaths.
In the PALM study, ZMapp served as the control, meaning the scientists used it as the baseline and compared the three other treatments with it.
USA Gymnastics supports the letter from the United States Olympic Committee and accepts it as an absolute necessity that the Olympic family advocates for a safe environment for all of our athletes.
We agree with the statement of the USOC that the interests of our athletes and clubs and their sport are better served by promoting meaningful changes within our organization rather than decertifying.
USA Gymnastics supports an independent investigation that could shed light on how abuse on the scale so bravely described by the survivors of Larry Nassar could go undetected for so long, and welcomes all necessary and appropriate changes.
USA Gymnastics and the USOC share the same goal - to make gymnastics and other sports as safe as possible for the athletes, so they can pursue their dreams in a secure, positive, and self-determined environment.
